First, we realize that $\cos^3(x)$ is just shorthand for $(\cos(x))^3$, which is clearly composite:

$f(x)=\underbrace{(~\overbrace{\cos(x)}^{\text{inner}}~)^3}_{\text{outer}}$

So if $f(x)=w(u(x))$, then:

$\begin{align}
\goldD{u(x)}&=\goldD{\cos(x)} &&\text{inner function}
\\\\
w(x)&=x^3&&\text{outer function}
\end{align}$

Before applying the chain rule, let's find the derivatives of the inner and outer functions (work not shown, but hopefully these derivatives are familiar by now).

$\begin{align}
\maroonD{u'(x)}&=\maroonD{-\sin(x)}
\\\\
\blueD{w'(x)}&=\blueD{3x^2}
\end{align}$

Now let's apply the chain rule:

$\begin{align}
f'(x)&=\dfrac{d}{dx}\left[w\Bigl(u(x)\Bigr)\right]
\\\\
&=\blueD{w'\Bigl(\goldD{u(x)}\Bigr)}\cdot\maroonD{u'(x)}
\\\\
&=\blueD{3(\goldD{\cos(x)})^2} \cdot \maroonD{-\sin(x)}
\\\\
&=-3\sin(x)\cos^2(x)
\end{align}$

